snippet.textDisplay: I used to work for GM and had one of these as a company car.  It was terrible... floaty bouncy ride and they also had a lot of trouble with those huge front windscreens, they would get wavy and distorted.  Ours had that issue and I used to get car sick when driving it.  GM also didn't sell many of these because Chrysler's vans were both cheaper and more innovative when it came to family-friendly features like seating, cupholders, dual rear doors earlier on, etc.  GM tried to be innovative with the dustbusters but they just weren't well executed.  Instead of learning the right lesson, they went uber conservative with the second generation vans and just failed to keep up with the market.  They never really tried again and completely ceded that market to Chrysler and the imports.

snippet.textDisplay: We had a 1990 Lumina APV when I was a kid. It looked cool at the time and there were some neat ideas in there. I remember only seeing Silhouettes once or twice in town. I didn't know they were making these as late as 96! We referred to our gray Lumina as the Space Roach, a name made more appropriate as the paint began to peel from the roof and hood. Quality of the GM builds at the time were pretty shoddy and their reputation was well deserved. I learned how to drive in one of these things and I've bought Japanese cars ever since. The sloping roof made them really hard to park, couldn't see your front end. New passengers would almost always hit their heads on the top of the door, THE PROBLEMS WERE REAL. The removable seats made them awesome for carrying stuff because even though it was underpowered, removing the seats got rid of like 2-300 lbs of weight (which doesn't happen in fold-down vehicles). So if you just needed one seat in the back, you could leave it there and get better performance / mileage. Removing the seats also gave you pretty great vertical clearance, it was almost like driving a covered minitruck in that configuration. Thanks for bringing back the memories of this jalopy! Would love to see a Burning Man version with tank treads.

snippet.textDisplay: Pardon my language, but it was also the worst piece of shit that Oldsmobile had ever built ever since they begin production! I Purchased the exact same model year as the one in this video in 2000, thinking I was going to get a great deal because I got it for next to nothing. My next-door neighbor, who was an elderly gentleman, had lost his drivers license, so he had to sell his car, and knowing that I needed a car, he gave it to me for only $3000. I will say this much in favour of it, I’ve never driven a vehicle that had more options in my life! It was fully loaded with every conceivable option you could possibly imagine (especially the power sliding doors, which was a huge deal back then, because no other minivan had them), it had plenty of power, and it only had....ready?……........25,000 km! He only ever used it to drive to the grocery store and back, he said the longest trip he ever took in it was from here, Toronto, to Niagara Falls and back, which is only an hour and a half drive. This vehicle was show room new, and he babied that car. Even though it was 4 years old when I got it, it still had all the original sticks, And even had the original plastic on the back seats, because he was a widower with no children. I thought I was the luckiest guy on earth to get this vehicle for so cheap, especially considering that it’s value, given its condition and mileage, was valued at $6500 (I think...can’t remember the exact price). I know that he never had one single problem with the vehicle, because I spoke to the man every day of my life, I always felt so sorry for him because he was alone, so I would go to his house every day to make sure he was OK. Sadly, he suffered a massive heart attack and died only two months after buying the car off of him, and I swear to God the car mourned his death. About a week after he died, the car began falling apart. First the transmission went, then the fan belts broke, and the radiator cracked open!....then came along 4 flat tires after some jack ass took a knife to all the tires in a Walmart parking lot while I was shopping. I can’t blame the tire thing on a mechanical default, but that’s only the beginning. From that point on words, I swear to god that car was in the shop more than it was on the road. The electronics on board were completely fried, the tachometer, speedometer, fuel gauges, radio, and everything else run by the computer, just stopped working, costing me a small fortune to repair. I hung onto it for quite a while, because even after paying for all those repairs, it was still cheaper then if I had paid full price for it, also, I just couldn’t leave it, because I felt like I would be Letting the gentleman who I got it from down, which I know sounds ridiculous, but he was such a sweet man, and his death hit me a lot harder than I thought it would. But the final nail in the coffin was when the oil pan literally fell off as I was driving down the highway. It was too weird, and it wasn’t because I was an abusive driver, if anything, I remember when he was driving it, he thought he was in the Indy 500, and used to floor The gas, and hit the brakes really hard, he would turn the corners like he was driving a Ferrari, I was actually a little bit afraid to be in the car when he was driving it, but that’s another reason why I bought it, because I felt it had been sufficiently broken in. But after the oil pan fell out, and don’t ask me how in the hell that happened, (when they put it up on the hoist, I could see it for myself, all the bolts holding it on had broken off, almost as if someone took a hammer and chisel to them). It was the strangest goddamn thing I’ve ever seen, so I told my mechanic just do the best you can for as cheap as you can because I was going to Get rid of it. Oddly enough, my mechanic decided to buy it from me for the exact same amount that I paid for it. Because he owns the garage, he was able to fix it up and resell it for more than double the value he got it, but I wasn’t willing to hold onto it any longer, especially because it was in the middle of winter, and the last thing I wanted was a car that kept breaking down when it was -20°C! I think my biggest pet peeve of all was trying to clean that damn dashboard, it had such a long front, you could never reach the window, and for the same reasons the defrost was useless, and on cold days, half the front window would still be frozen. Like I said it was powerful enough, and it did have a really smooth ride, plus all the bells and whistle’s, which was an added bonus, dare I say it was actually ahead of its time. But I guess it just didn’t like me, and I would never buy another one as long as I live! After I sold it I bought myself a Ford Windstar, best thing I ever did, that was a wonderful van, and it lasted me for years. Right now I’m driving a 2006 Ford 500 that I inherited from my father after he just bought himself a brand new Taurus, but I have to say that Ford makes some pretty good cars. Considering it’s 14 years old, like the old man I bought the Oldsmobile from, my father rarely drives, and even though it’s 14 years old it only had 70 000 km on it. I’ve had it for two years, and the only thing I’ve had to do was put new tires on and give it an oil change every 5000 km like I do with with every vehicle I own. It’s funny that you mention the Dustbuster thing, because that’s exactly what all of my friends used to call it, I guess it kind of did look like one, but I think in retrospect, Oldsmobile should have stuck to what they are best at, old man cars! I don’t even think there’s any left on the road, at least not here in Toronto, but I would never ever advise anyone to buy one unless they want to pay a fortune in repairs every few weeks!

snippet.textDisplay: In 1990, my graduation year, the 3 GM vans debuted.  I positively loved these vehicles, namely the Silhouette and TransSport. Listed it in my "senior year memory book" as my favorite car. They were, unfortunately, underpowered until 3800 V6 was introduced for the vans. The 3.1 liters were subject to transmission issues, too. I had a college professor who owned a red Silhouette.  Because he had seen my personal car was ALWAYS clean and shiny, he asked I detail his. Their crash test results, being kind, were positively terrible (watch YouTube videos of TransSport and Montana crash test...IIHS, I believe).

I have had the Pontiac 1994 version that is very similar to this one.

I drove 145.000 km without any problems with normal maintenance.
New price in the Netherlands with LPG was around 38.600 (!) euro's.
It was the fastest (0-100kmh) minivan available at the time, and what I can remember he drove backwards really fast ;-)
I found the automatic level control behind a plus.
Downside was indeed the tip of the door and the strange position behind the wheel.
Nice car, had fun with it.
Sold it after 4y for 18.500 euro's
Thanks for the review.

snippet.textDisplay: I LOVED my Silhouette. I bought it used for $500.00. Had to put a radiator in it, but I knew it needed one when I bought it. And it needed a new seal on the side door, which I also knew... that seal turned out to be harder to find that I bargained for, and it took me about 3-4 months to find a dealer that actually still had one in stock, and this was about 10 years ago, I imagine parts are near unobtainium for these now. Drove it for 4 years and sold it for $750.00. Wish I'd kept it, honestly. Mine had cloth seats instead of leather, and it had the 3800 V6. Mine was a sort of mint green metallic with the stripe package. No power sliding door on mine. It was a rattle trap because it hadn't been taken well care of, so lots of squeaks and rattles because of those large plastic interior pieces, but it was a great vehicle. The seats DID fold flat, though, they just didn't fold down to the floor. The factory seat backs would fold down flat so you could put stuff across the top of them. It was very comfortable as far as riding down the road. The 3800 was a little easier to work on than the other motors, but not a lot. I'd buy one again if I could find one. There are a couple of them still rolling around in my town. Unfortunately the guy who bought mine started letting his kid drive it, and it got totaled in an accident from what i was told.
snippet.textOriginal: I LOVED my Silhouette.  I bought it used for $500.00.  Had to put a radiator in it, but I knew it needed one when I bought it.  And it needed a new seal on the side door, which I also knew... that seal turned out to be harder to find that I bargained for, and it took me about 3-4 months to find a dealer that actually still had one in stock, and this was about 10 years ago, I imagine parts are near unobtainium for these now.  Drove it for 4 years and sold it for $750.00.  Wish I'd kept it, honestly.  Mine had cloth seats instead of leather, and it had the 3800 V6.  Mine was a sort of mint green metallic with the stripe package.  No power sliding door on mine.  It was a rattle trap because it hadn't been taken well care of, so lots of squeaks and rattles because of those large plastic interior pieces, but it was a great vehicle.  The seats DID fold flat, though, they just didn't fold down to the floor.  The factory seat backs would fold down flat so you could put stuff across the top of them.  It was very comfortable as far as riding down the road.  The 3800 was a *little* easier to work on than the other motors, but not a lot.  I'd buy one again if I could find one.  There are a couple of them still rolling around in my town.  Unfortunately the guy who bought mine started letting his kid drive it, and it got totaled in an accident from what i was told.

snippet.textDisplay: You did not add that it had all plastic panels that didn’t get dings or rot. A deer ran into the front fender and caused a big dent, next day it completely went back to normal. You will never find dings,dents or rust on panels and if you find one today the body will look great. It had a air cleaner located in the back glove compartment that they recommended changing every 6 months. Captain chairs armrest and a air compressor with coiled hose that could reach all tires (located side panel in rear). Under carpet it had a very thick padding which made the van very quiet. Everything else you mentioned was correct.

snippet.textDisplay: My Pontiac Transport was the worst vehicle I've ever owned. Rear main seal failed, but the leak was kind of slow. The oil pan gasket failed (weird!) and unlike most vehicles that was major cost to fix (doh!). We donated the van as a mechanics special. (With a full complement of grey leather seats!) The most weird of those GM vans, IMHO, was the Pontiac Transport with the offroad trim.
